column168: A Clean Harbors tractor and trailer were parked inside secondary containment at loading dock at the Clean Harbors facility in Baltimore MD.The fork truck driver was  offloading pallets of 5 gallon pails when one fork punctured the side of a 5 gallon steel container. The fork truck driver immediately removed fork truck, put down absorbant pads and spill booms inside trailer. Fork truck driver contacted supervisor and shipper project manager. Response personnel cleaned up spillage donning the proper PPE and placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. The spill was fully captured inside of the van trailer, no waste hit the secondary containment area of the loading dock.
column169: The container was damaged due to operator error and him not being able to see as the loading dock was not covered and operators glasses were comprimised by heavy rain. In order to prevent a recurrence, the plant forklift operator was spoken with and is being retrained regarding the importance of safe forklift operation and preventing these type of incidences from reoccuring.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Residue tank car CSOX 23641 in the railyard was reported emanating an odor. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected CSOX 23641 and reported finding the applied manway nozzle gasket torn (approximately half its circumference was torn) and not sealing. The responders installed a new manway gasket and resecured the manway cover. Afterwards, no commodity odor was detectable. Intact shipper seal UNIVAR USA 017430 at the manway cover was replaced with seal BNSF 06157724.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: October 3, 2013: At 2:47PM, during a routine tour/inspection of Conrail's Port Richmond Yard,  Philadelphia, PA, Norfolk Southern Police Department Special Agent M. Lesinski contacted CR Risk Manager A. Richter, advising of product residue on both sides of tank car GATX 45052, load, Sodium Hydroxide, Solution.  Car was located on the Speedway Track in the yard.    Further inspection by CR Mechanical General Foreman S. Hart, and CR emergency response contractor Hepaco-React's S. Gould, noted the 165 pound safety vent frangible disc (stainless steel) had ruptured as designed at some point during transportation.  Estimate approximately 1-2 gallons of release on the car.  No product noted on the ground in and around the tank car.  The ruptured stainless steel disc was replaced in kind, and the rest of the tank car was inspected with no further exceptions noted.  Car was moved from Port Richmind Yard down to "E" Yard (an extension of the Port Richmond Yard, near the Ann Street Shop) and was decontaminated/cleaned the following day (October 4, 2013) by Hepaco-React personnel.  Car was later okayed for forwarding to original destination, Westway Terminals, Philadelphia, PA, for unloading.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The shipment was tendered in SEA. An accepting agent seeing it was a type of electronic equipment asked if there were any batteries. The driver did not know but called the shipper. They returned the call and stated there were no batteries, lithium or otherwise. There is no indication in the AWB that there are batteries either.  Shen the shipment was screened it was found to contain several 150Wh lithium batteries. The boxes containing them had the proper hazard label, however they were completely covered with another shipping label.  The shipment is held in the warehouse. Pictures taken.
column169: Follow proper procedures for shipping batteries.  All the boxes were correct, they just needed the proper documentation.

column168: A driver was at the shipper's location waiting while the shipper loaded his tanker with hazardous waste.  When the tanker was ready to go, the person who was loading it advised the driver that he had accidentally overfilled it but offloaded some of the material.  The driver proceeded out of the gate and realized he left something in the scale house.  At that time, he observed liquid coming out of the vent cap.  He then re-entered the plant to have another 400 pounds of the material removed.  The overfilled material evaporated without any residue being left on the tanker or the ground.  The tanker then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The person loading the material was also loading a railcar at the same time and not fully concentrating on the loading of the tanker.  His supervisor was made aware of the situation at the time and cautioned the loading personnel to use caution when loading vehicles.

column168: A tanker was being loaded at the shipper's location from a frac tank.  When the loading was complete, the driver and another employee unhooked the hose from the frac tank.  They lost vacuum and the backwash from the hose splashed onto the ground and a subcontractor employee who was standing there.  The valve was then immediately closed, the subcontractor changed out of his personal protective equipment and a response crew was called to clean up the spilled material, which was placed into a drum along with a shovelful of gravel and left on site.  The tanker then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: Hose and line clearing procedures were reviewed with all employees involved.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS in regards to a battery acid release in a trailer. Apparently during transit, the pallet the battery was on was defective resulting in the battery tipping over. The contractor re-secured the battery, neutralized the released material and swept the impacted areas clean. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

A flatbed trailer containing 16 totes of a liquid hazardous waste was parked at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  During a routine yard check, it was noticed that one of the totes was leaking material onto the ground.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found that one of the totes had a closure that had not been tightened.  The material was cleaned up with a suitable absorbant material and a shovelful of dirt from the ground was picked up.  The dirt and cleanup material was placed into the tote and it was closed properly.  The load then was taken to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver who picked up the material was cautioned to insure all closures are properly closed per the container closure specifications.

column168: On Tuesday, October 1st, 2013, at 0312 hours, personnel in the CSXT Russell/Big Four Yard discovered GATX 61200, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid leaking from the top of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper AXIALL Corp. representative Larry Bergstrom, cell 304-266-8294 was notified. CHEMTREC report 2013-10-01-00018 was filed. Quick Response Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene, and found the Salco Non-Reclosing Pressure Relief Device - frangible disc housing venting vapors, upon inspection the frangible disc was ruptured. Special Professional Services, Inc. was dispatched to remove and replace the frangible disc, it was completed on 10/01/2013 at 1300 hours.  The release was secured and the tank car was release for transit.      Cause Code: 441  NARRI:  5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On 10/02/2013 at 13:17, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard, Waycross GA discovered GAMX 90028, a residue tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied Petroleum Gas Liquefied, leaking from vapor line valve. The car was isolated and Targa Transport, GA EPD, NRC and Chemtrec were notified. CHEMTREC Report #2013100200195. Josh Winters, a CSXT manager, was dispatched to the scene and found a vapor release from the vapor line valve and the sample line plug area. Mr. Winters found that both valves not fully closed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper contact Dave Lindow 713-826-2685.The valve was closed and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 145  NARRI:5(4+5+0) x (2+0) = 90

column168: On 10/07/2013 at 17:55, personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard, Waycross Georgia discovered ACFX 73062, a residue tank car of DICYCLOPENTADIENE, leaking from vapor line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper Richhold and Chemtrec were notified. CHEMTREC Report # 2013-1007-00178. Josh Winters a CSXT manager, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line partially open and plug out and the manway not properly secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper MARK DUBOIS, REICHOLD 919-990-7825. The vapor line valve was closed, plug secured and the manway was properly secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:390  NARRI:5(4+1+0) x (2+0)=50

column168: The undeclared hazmat was found during screening and the FAA was notified.

On October 7, 2013, a 260 gallon tote of UN1840 Zinc Chloride Solution experienced a leak from the bottom of the tote due to too much weight being stacked on top of it. The incident resulted in the release of an estimated two gallons of the material onto the dock. The tote was positioned over a recovery drum while a contractor was on the way to transfer the material. The contractor transferred the material into a new tote and wiped out the less than half gallon of material that had accumulated in the recovery drum. The damaged tote and pads were staged on site to be sent back to the shipper. The material that had released onto the dock was dried by the time the contractor had arrived onsite.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: UTLX 220853 was found with product visible on the top of the car extending approximately three feet down the side.  Upon inspection, product was visible on the top of the pressure plate and was also bubbling by the threads on the liquid valve plug.  The plug was checked and was able to be removed  by hand.  The ball valve inside the liquid valve appeared to have debris between the ball and the valve body.  The car was temporarily secured by reinstalling the plug with new teflon tape.  The shipper was contacted and will coordinate repairs and/or a OTMA request.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF train, intermodal trailer RDWY 290412 was observed with a paint like substance leaking from within this trailer. RDWY 290412 was taken to the facility's containment area for further inspection. Shipper contract responders reported that 4 five gallon steel pails were compromised during in transit load shifting which resulted from insufficient blocking and bracing of the lading. The pails were partially crushed by adjacent palletized lading that shifted.  Responders placed the compromised pails into recovery drums for return to the intermodal shipper. Spillage on the exterior and inside RDWY 290412 was cleaned. Afterwards, lading removed from RDWY 290412 was returned, properly blocked and braced for further transit.  Spent cleaning materials were placed into a disposal drum and earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's loading arrangements include safeguards to prevent lading from falling onto or sliding into other lading during normal or expected movement conditions encountered during transportation.

column25: RPMG Inc. by Dakota Ethanol LLC
column168: Tank car NATX 303555 was reported expelling a small amount of commodity from its manway closure during movement in the railyard. NATX 303555 was carefully moved and isolated at the facility's repair track. No further commodity release was observed when NATX 303555 remained motionless. Contract responders inspecting NATX 303555 reported finding all six manway securement bolts not tool tight (four of these bolts were only hand tight). Intact shipper seal numbered 034968 was removed in order to inspect the condition of the applied manway gasket and the gasket was deemed serviceable. The responders properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts and applied seal HMRI 00360 at the manway closure. All spillage on the tank shell either evaporated or was washed away by recent rain events. No ground impact from spillage was reported.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A hard coupling occurred on the hump at the A+S yard causing a surge of product.  The surge forced the pressure relief device (reclosing) to open and release less than one quart of HCL into the combination housing and top of the rail car. The pressure relief device closed, stopping the release.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services was at Clean Harbors itransit facility in Wheeling WV. The driver doing a routine inspection saw that one  container had a pin hole leak in the top chime of a drum. Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. Norguay Tech was contacted and advised of the leaking drum and requested to check any more drums they have for integrity of the chimes.

column168: At 5:10 pm.  Facility personell noticed a smoking van at the Clean Harbors Baltimore plant after it had arrived from the Anne Andrundel Household Hazardous Waste collection.  Apparently, some oxidizers got wet and built up pressing blowing the lid off a container.  No one hurt, nothing damaged.  Clean Harbors Field services called in to isolate and re-package container after lid blew and reaction appeared complete.  The Maryland Department of Environment was notified by Clean Harbors plant compliance officer.
column169: Clean Harbors conducted an internal review of the incident and concluded that moisture was likly present in the drum due to rain that day during the Household Hazardous waste collection. A Clean Harbors review team evaluated several options to minimize the handling of oxidizers during waste collections and decided that oxidizers will be packed in sealable water resistant containers until they can be sorted and packaged properly to avoid the possibility of getting the product wet. Also the drums would be filled with vermiculite as an added security measure.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Vapor Valve
column62: Missing Component or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: Tank car PROX 45665 was reported emanating a 'gasoline' type odor in the railyard. Inspection of PROX 45665 by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed all valves appeared closed and no liquid commodity release was observed. The vapor valve's closure plug was found not properly applied. This closure plug was resting atop the vapor valve's closure orifice with no plug threads threaded. The responder properly applied the vapor valve's closure plug and tool tightened this plug into its threaded closure orifice. Afterwards, the commodity odor dissipated and became non-detectable. Intact shipper seal numbered 0000050 at the valve housing cover was replaced by seal BNSF HAZMAT 001777.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car PROX 98351 was reported emanating a gasoline odor in the railyard. column168: AN INCIDENT OCCURED IN THE LOCK HAVEN YARD LOCATED ON THE  NITTANY & BALD EAGLE RAILROAD, WHICH IS AN AFFILIATED RAILROAD OF THE PARENT COMPANY (NORTH SHORE RAILROAD COMPANY.) THE YARD CONDUCTOR DISCOVERED A MINOR DIP COMING FROM THE DOME AREA OF THE CAR AND IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR RAIL SECURITY COORDINATOR AND NSHR SENIOR MANAGEMENT OFFICIALS. WITH THE AUTHORIZATION OF THE LOCK HAVEN FIRE CHIEF WHO HAD ASSUMED COMMAND, AVERY DENNISON EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WALKED TO THE RAIL CAR TO FIND TWO BUCKETS, PLACED BY THE NBER GENERAL MANAGER, UNDER THE RAIL CAR COLLECTING DRIPS OF BUTYL ACRYLATE ORIGINATING FROM THE DOME AREA OF RAIL CAR GATX 53695. THE ATMOSPHERE WAS CONFIRMED TO BE BELOW THE ACGIH TWA OF 2 PPM. AN AVERY DENNISON RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND INVESTIGATED. BUTYL ACRYLATE WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM A GAP BETWEEN THE RAIL CARM, DOME, MANWAY PLATE AND THE DIP TUBE VALVE HOUSING. ALL FOUR NUTS HOLDING THE VALVE TO THE MANWAY PLATE WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE BUTYL ACRYLATE STOPPED DRIPPING FROM THE MANWAY PLATE. PIGMATS WERE USED TO ABSORB LIQUID IN THE DOME AREA. CONTAMINATED PIGMATS AND APPROXIMATELY HALF A PINT OF BUTYL ACRYLATE THAT WAS COLLECTED IN THE BUCKETS BENEATH THE RAIL CAR WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT THE AVERY DENNISON FACILITY.
column169: ALL EMPLOYEES OF THE NORTH SHORE RAILROAD COMPANY ARE TRAINED ON OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECURITY PLAN FILED WITH FRA, TSA, PHMSA, WHICH INCLUDES EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES. IN THIS INSTANCE, THE YARD CONDUCTOR DISCOVERED THE LEAKING MATERIAL AND FOLLOWED PROPER PROTOCOL IN ACCORDANCE WITH OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.

column168: An employee forked the valve of the tote while it was staged on the dock. The chemical was released in the surrounding area and was slowed down by the use of oil dry. None of the chemical went off the dock. The tote was forked near the valve and the chemical was released. The duration of the release was approx 15 minutes prior to contacting safety department. Emergency response vendor (ERV) was contacted to come out and clean spill.  RQ reported by shipper to be 86,553 lbs.  Further details of clean up, package capacity and amount released provided by ERV.   ERV reported that an estimated 200-250 gallons had been released from the tote, by the time of arrival, which was estimated at 500 gallons. All material was contained to the dock.   A notification to the NRC was be made regarding this material release due to to potential for RQ threshold exceedence.   The Mecklenberg County LEPC was notified of this release. A message was left with the county EMA director   The ERV reported that they were able to secure the release by shutting off a secondary valve on the tote. The ERV reported that they had attempted to pump off the material but it was too late. The ERV reported they lost the entire contents of the material onto the dock. The ERV reported that they had placed the tote onto a pallet with absorbent pads under it. The ERV applied additional absorbents to the impacted area of the dock.   The ERV reported that the clean up was finished. The ERV reported that 5 drums and the damaged tote were staged on site to be managed onsite following waste disposal process. Cost reserve for cleanup $4000.

column168: During a DOT inspection the officer noticed a small amount of liquid dripping from the rear of a Clean Harbors Van trailer. The driver opened the door and the leaking drum was at the rear of the trailer so the driver padded the area and placed a bucket under the dripping area. Local Fire, Police and Haz Mat Departments were notified and responded to the site. The rest area was closed for approximatly 2 hours in order to keep the area clear from public access. The drum was placed in a salvage drum provided on the underside of the trailer and the material was cleaned up donning the proper personal protective equipment and put into the salvage drum. It was discovered that the drum had a one inch tear on the bottom of the drum.  The van trailer was release by the DOT officer for continued transportation to its intended disposal facility. NY DEC was notified (Report 1307521) and the NRC (Report 1063690)  .
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. It is suspected that the drum hit the corner of a pallet during transfer loading causing the puncture. The Clean Harbors facility that loaded the drum was notified and advised to alert personell of loading procedures.

column168: The substance came in on inbound 2893 which arrived in from CLT. The Jetstream employee who noticed the substance under the bag was Andreary Turner who was the person that loaded and unloaded the cargo bin. Ms. Turner states that she noticed the substance and said that it looked like a powdery flour substance that had the imagery of cocaine. She had gloves on during the whole load/unload process and basically took the bag which was about one-fourth full and placed it on the belt loader.  She did not immediately notify any supervision of the substance until four hours later to Ryan Buckner who later got with the Airport police who later had the substance reviewed. A call was received from Moreau at 0241am advising that the results from the Fire Department regarding the substance found it to be of hazardous material that is mostly used for batteries and if wet would be dangerous.
column169: Ms. Turner failed to follow proper procedures on reporting what seemed to be a suspicious item to Leadership immediately, therefore, her actions in regard to this will be handled accordingly by Emmett Winters immediately.   I will be revisiting the proper procedure to all personnel with a signoff to ensure that everybody is aware on the proper process when an unidentified item is located on or near an aircraft.

column168: Customer tendered the cargo for shipment at the GSP cargo facility and indicated on the air waybill no hazmat was contained in the shipment. column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was backed into the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into other trailers destined for various intended waste disposal facilities.  Prior to unloading, it was noticed that there was liquid material leaking from the trailer onto the concrete containment area beneath the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and repackaged the material into drums.  The absorbant material used to clean up the spilled material was placed into the drums along with the leaking super sacks.  The LA State police were called--incident number 13-04811.
column169: The material was a solid sludge like material that had not been thoroughly solidified--causing liquid to leak out of the sack.  The origin location was advised to contact the customer to advise them to review their solidification procedures and not ship this material unless better steps are taken.

column169: The drum was not leaking at the time of pickup, but did show signs of aging.  The driver and shipper will be cautioned to use better care in choosing and accepting old containers for use in transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste at the intermediate truck transfer facility was being unloaded for consolidation into a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  The forklift operator misjudged his clearance and punctured a drum with the forklift blade.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean up the trailer floor.  The shipment was then loaded without further incident.
column169: The forklift operator was advised to use better care and caution when loading and unloading drums.  He will be scheduled for retraining this week and cannot operate the forklift until training is completed.

column169: Better education to shippers on proper classification if ID8000.

column168: The loader was loading another pallet omn the trailer and the fork blades were sticking thru the end of the pallet when the blades struck the drum on the bottom above the bottom ring. The drum was placed in a neutral position to stop the leak and the free liquid was covered with dry earth material and swept up then placed in a recovery drum. The spill was managed in 2 hours from the intiail relaese and all waste was properly disposed of accordng to local and federal regulations.

column168: On 10/5/2013, at 02:14 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard Big Four discovered TILX110161, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid, leaking from a hole in the vapor space B-end just above the reporting marks.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Bayer Material Science, and Hendricks Communication Center were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2013100500017. Summit, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a penny size hole on the top of the B-end, about 5 feet from the catwalk before the lettering on the car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Bayer Material Science ,Chad Blake, 412-777-7475. Contractor personnel patched the hole and transloaded the product from TILX110161 into tank car TILX111099.  TILX110161 was decontaminated and placed on hold awaiting for a OTMA-1 for the car to be sent to Brewton, AL for repairs.    This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 656  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) X (2+5)=140
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Driver was unloading dyed diesel fuel at a farm site. After unloading, the driver unhooked his hose from the tank and the check valve failed causing 10 gallons of diesel fuel to spill on to a gravel surface. The contaminated soil was removed and remediated through an enviromental clean up agency.
column169: We contacted the farmer owned tank and the farmer agreed to replace the faulty valve and replace it with a manual shut off valve that can be controlled by the driver.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On 10/14/2013, at 12:26 hrs., a Trainmaster at the CSXT St. Clair yard, St. Clair, MI reported the pressure housing opened and what appeared to be vapors coming from TILX 303395, a residue tank car of UN1075, Liquefied Petroleum Gas. As per St. Clair yard personnel, the tank car was not in this state prior and they suspect vandalism on TILX 303395. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Growmark (Marysville Underground), was notified via CHEMTREC, report #2013-10-14-00114 . EQ, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the sample line open and the plug removed. Upon further inspection, identified both the vapor line valve and the "B" end liquid line valve in the open position with no product release due to properly secured secondary plugs on both valves. The shipper representative, Eric Metedia, (810) 488-0120 was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and TILX 303395 was released for disposition. CSXT Police investigation report #13101734 is still pending in regards to this open incident.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 2x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 36  Cause code:513
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: On 10/18/2013 at approximately 08:41 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Clifton Forge, VA yard discovered ROCX 1009, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Enterprise Products, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified via CHEMTREC Report #2013-10-18-00058. Enterprise Products (Helen Johannes 713-381-8291) advised they were only the loader of the car and that CSX needed to contact Centennial Energy (Deb Hughes 720-889-3665). HEPACO and WEL, CSXT emergency response contractors, were dispatched to the scene and found a bent leaking sample line. Contractor personnel applied the midland kit to confine the release awaiting the arrival of an empty tank car. The empty tank car arrived and tank car ROCX 1009 was transferred into CTCX 780184. The pressure was flared off ROCX 1009 and the sample line was removed and a stainless steel plug was put in its place. The threads on the sample line appear to be bent, therefore. a not seated properly sample line. Centennial Energy has applied for an OTMA to have ROCX 1009 sent to a home shop to be repaired.     This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: =512  NARRI: 2X(5+5+0)X(2+0)=40
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 25, 2013 at approximately 14:14 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Bayview Yard discovered GATX 60358, a loaded tank car of Sulphur Molten, with a vapor odor coming from the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, CHEMTRADE, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified. CHEMTRADE emergency number was contacted and spoke to Randy Theriot (409-728-3877) and CSX was contacted back by Sharon Carey (416-640-8125) from CHEMTRADE.  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one of 6 manway cover bolts less than tool tight and a gasket was found to be ripped and torn. HEPACO personnel tightened the manway cover bolt and applied a new gasket and the odor was no longer present. The car was secured and released on to the consignee.    This incident did not require a special switching move    Cause Code: 209  NARRI:  5X(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 7, 2013, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the Shipper (Dufry American Services Inc) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container FSCU631423-0 (UN1266 PERFUMERY PRODUCTS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. On the same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

column168: The unit involved in the incident on 10/10/2013 was traveling on a 4 lane divided hi-way at posted speed of 65mph. As it entered a slight right curve the unit left the roadway going off the berm into the median. The driver attempted to steer the unit to the right slightly re-entering the roadway causing the unit to rollover. The unit was severely damaged and was leaking product. The driver was wearing his seat belt. He exited the unit and 911 was called. The EMA, Local VFD's, PASP, NRC, DEP, PEMA, and wrecker service were all notified. Product was leaking from the dome lid area as it was crushed from the rollover. The product leakage was contained by dirt being placed in the direction of flow. Two wreckers were then used to upright the unit which stopped the leakage.  The duration of leakage was approximately three hours. 833 gallons per hour or 13.89 gallons per minute. The product was left in place to cool and solidify for 24 hours as it posed no environmental threat. It was then removed with limited amount of soil. The area was cleared of debris and restored to it's natural state. All first responders and emergency crews are to be commended for their actions through the duration of this incident.
column169: Our company utilizes several forms of online and hands on training materials provided by PERS, J.J. Keller & Associates, Acuity Insurance Co., and various other sources. Our main priority is safety and compliance, which is a never ending daily process. The safety of our drivers is most important as is the safety of the general public who travel the same hi ways as we do. As every company knows, you only have control over your drivers while they are on duty as your employee. It is difficult to regulate their off duty hours. You provide the necessary training to help them realize the importance of their personal time and hope they use it in a beneficial manner. The unit that was damaged, resulting in leakage of product, did remain structurally sound. An emergency shut off valve on the vent system was manually closed to prevent further leakage from that point. The rollover protection box was crushed. This caused a deformity to the dome lid area where the leakage occurred. Immediate action and response is very important in minimizing leakage through containment and shutting off the source.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Entrained tank car GATX 34188 on an inbound BNSF through train on the departure track in the railyard was reported venting with 'frost' observed on the valve housing nozzle. BNSF and contract responders inspecting GATX 34188 reported finding both liquid valves' and the vapor valve's closure plugs loose (only hand tight). Icing was observed accumulating around the B-end liquid valve's closure plug area with the valve in the closed position, therefore some residue commodity vapors were by-passing this closed valve. This liquid valve's closure plug was removed and new Teflon tape applied to its threaded area, reinserted and properly tool tightened. The other closure plugs were also properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no further vapor venting was evident when leak tests were completed. The icing at the valve housing area evaporated. Response was concluded by 0845 hrs. CDT, 10/30/2013.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s disposal facility. During a routine load inspection the driver discovered that a drum was leaking slowly from the body of the container. The driver contacted local fire and dispatch and response personnel were dispatched. They placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum and cleaned the area, placed all clean-up debris from the van trailer in the salvage drum and secured it for continued transportation. The NY DEC was notified and a DEC agent went to the spill site (Report #1307724)and was satisfied with the clean up and released the vehicle.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transporttion, no evidence of leaking was observed. It is believed that the that during transpotation an object on the floor gouged the bottom of the container allowing the material to leak from the container. In order to prevent a recurrence, the individuals that offered the  shipment for transportation and the driver in posession of the shipment have been re instructed to ensure that each drum is inspected before it is accepted  for transportation. Any container that is found to have suspect structural integrity is to be either transferred into a suitable container or placed into a  salvage drum for continued transportation.

column168: Waste material was loaded at generator and inspected by driver during loading.  Truck then proceeded from the facility on return delivery route on Hwy 49 north out of Gulfport,MS.  Driver was proceeding northbound at the speedlimit when a car pulled out of a side road onto the the Highway.  The Rineco Transportation driver applied the brakes with the full stopping force available to him.  The driver stated in the post interview that he could not believe that the tractor had not struck the car.  The material in the back of the trailer being liquid in nature shifted forward.  The sum force of the materials inertia was transfered to the drums in the front of the trailer.  The bungs from these first drums were shot out of the drums and the rocking back of the material.  The drums were aslo crushed thus releasing the material from the implosion of the volume.
column169: Interviews and a report were taken from the driver as our company protocol.  There is nothing that leads us to believe that this was nothing but a random occurance due to the driver being cutoff by another vehicle.

column168: AS TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS TRAVELING ON I-20 IN TEXAS, A MECHANICAL FAILURE OCCURRED SOMEWHERE WITHIN THE TRAILER RIGHT FRONT TANDEM (TIRE-BRAKE-HUB) AREA. THE DRIVER WAS WARNED BY A PASSING MOTORIST OF SMOKE AND PULLED THE UNIT TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED A FIRE HAD ERUPTED FROM THE WHEEL AREA. THE DRIVER MADE AN ATTEMPT TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITH A PORTABLE FIRE EXTINGUISHER BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. THE LOCAL SHERIFF ARRIVED ON SCENE AND REMOVED THE DRIVER FROM THE AREA AND WAITED ON THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE. ON BOARD WERE FIVE IBC'S CONTAINING REGULATED CHEMICALS, TWO IBC'S CONTAINING UN1814 WERE FAR ENOUGH FORWARD ON THE TRAILER THAT THEY WERE UNHARMED BY THE FIRE. ONE IBC OF UN1230, BEING OF STAINLESS STEEL CONSTRUCTION WAS ALSO UNHARMED. THE TWO IBC'S IN QUESTION WERE OF PLASTIC CONSTRUCTION AND BOTH CONTAINED UN1230 CHEMICALS. THESE TWO IBC'S WERE CLOSEST TO THE FIRE AND WERE DESTROYED. OF THE TWO DESTROYED IBC'S, ONE CONTAINING 200 GALLONS OF UN1230 WAS COMPLETELY LOST DUE TO FIRE. ONE CONTAINING 310 GALLONS OF UN1230 LOST AN ESTIMATED 270 GALLONS DUE TO FIRE, AND 40 GALLONS TO THE GROUND AFTER FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED DUE TO THE EXTENSIVE DAMAGES TO THE PACKAGE. ATTEMPTS HAVE BEEN MADE TO COLLECT MANUFACTURERS INFORMATION FROM THE TWO DESTROYED IBC'S, HOWEVER THE MARKINGS WERE OBLITERATED BEYOND THE POINT OF RECOVERY. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THE TIME TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WAS A MINIMAL CONTRIBUTOR TO THE CLOSURE OF THE ROADWAY, AND THE MAJORITY OF THE TIME WAS SPENT ON REMEDIATION.
column169: AS FAR AS THE MECHANICAL FAILURE, THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGE HAS MADE IT CUMBERSOME TO IDENTIFY THE ROOT CAUSE IN ORDER TO DISCUSS CHANGES THAT WOULD HELP PREVENT A FUTURE OCCURRENCE. AS FAR AS THE PACKAGING, IT HAS BEEN NOTED THAT THE USE OF THE STAINLESS STEEL CONSTRUCTION IBC IN THIS PARTICULAR EVENT EVADED PRODUCT LOSS DUE TO FIRE AND HAS BEEN RECOMMENDED THAT AT MINIMUM THE CLASS 3 CHEMICALS WOULD BE BETTER SERVED IF TRANSPORTED IN IBC'S OF THIS CONSTRUCTION, BY DRAMATICALLY INCREASING THE LENGTH OF TIME FOR PACKAGE FAILURE DUE TO FIRE.

column168: Box was found to be leaking while unloading of a trailer. The chemical was contained and cleaned up in-house.
Undeclared hazmat discovered at Anchorage cargo. The FAA was notified.  Shipment originated in Nome and transported to Anchorage.

While a Veolia employee was offloading the container with a drum dolly, the bottom tines of the dolly punctured the side of the drum.  The employee immediately addressed the spill and repackaged the material in a DOT specification rated container.  The employee has been provided with a hands on training on the proper use of a drum dolly to prevent a reoccurrence.

column168: Driver was headed west on Wyo. 450; 6 miles west of Newcastle, WY when allegedly a driver entered his lane and forced him to leave the roadway or hit head on with the alleged vehicle. Vehicle went off the right shoulder then corrected back onto the highway causing the pup trailer to over correct and with product slosh tripped on the pavement and skidded down the shoulder of the roadway. The damage from hitting the pavement and the abrasive effect of the highway the skin was breached and allowed diesel to escape from the tank. The driver was able to keep the tractor and lead trailer upright and safely stop off the roadway.   The driver called 911 and reported the incident; then called Dixon Bros. Inc. dispatch office to report the accident. Driver observed some leakage and was instructed to use spill kit to protect any drainage area. EMS responded as well as I responded to the sight. Diesel was flowing out of the ruptured tank at a fairly rapid rate. A storm water drain (cross over culvert) was about 150’ from the spill point so dirt was put in the pipe to plug it preventing any diesel to enter and contaminate the other side of the roadway. A trench was dug to capture diesel and allow a vacuum truck to remove it as it collected in the trench. Approximately 17 barrels or 714 gallons were recovered by the vac truck. Spill duration was close to 2 hours.   The trailer that was overturned was evacuated by another Dixon Bros. truck that was dispatched to assist with the accident. Approximately 2169 gallons were recovered at the crash site from the overturned trailer that was delivered to the end user.   Remediation efforts started the following day with contaminated soil being dug up and stockpiled for transit. All materials were transported to Northeast Wyoming Soil and fresh fill and top soil was hauled in for remediation. Seeding has taken place and we are waiting for the Wyoming Department of Environmental Quality to send the necessary forms to close the incident.
column169: Truck drivers are being trained in quarterly safety meetings to use defensive driving techniques to keep from leaving the roadway when encountering obstacles in their lane. Response time and duties have been discussed to shorten duration of time from accident till company response vehicles are dispatched to the scene. This is subject to distance from terminal to crash site and measures already in place by responding EMS

column168: On October 18, 2013 at approximately 2100, a company driver had just loaded the W North 2-1N lease and was traveling on rural county road South 92 Dr. (unpaved) near Tonkawa, OK.  Road conditions were very slick and muddy due to recent heavy rain in the area.  While on the muddy road, the driver traveled slowly up a slight grade when the tires broke traction and begun to slide.  The driver stopped the unit completely and in doing so, the trailer slid toward the ditch.  The driver set the brakes on the truck, but the trailer continued to slide into a steep ditch until the fifth-wheel broke free and the trailer overturned.  The driver was not injured as a result of the trailer over-turning.  There was also no evidence that the cargo tank had been compromised.  The driver then reported the incident.    Company personnel responded to the scene and notifications were made to the Oklahoma Highway Patrol and Oklahoma Corporation Commission.  Recover services arrived on scene early the following morning and uprighted the trailer.  It was at that time, oil was discovered missing from the cargo tank.  After investigating, it was discovered that approximately 119 bbl of crude oil had released into very porous soil under the trailer with no visible free liquid on the surface. The release occurred over a duration of approximately 12 hours.  Futher investigation revealed the valve had not been damaged, but the valve handle had been forced open due to roll-over impact in the mud.  After the trailer was removed from the site, a State Registered Environmental Contractor excavated and removed the contaminated soil from the scene and disposed of it properly in the Davis Sanitary landfill near Tonkawa, OK.
column169: Company shall provide additional awareness training to drivers regarding Recognition of High Risk/Consequence Potential and Exercising Good Judgment when dealing with hazardous road conditions or other environmental factors.

column168: AS JCI JONES CHEMICALS INC DRIVER RUBEN BOBADILLA BEGAN HIS RIGHT TURN STOP LIGHT SIGNAL AT DENKER STREET ON TO TORRANCE BLVD AND CHECKING HIS RIGHT MIRROR FOR CLEARANCE OF TRAILER'S RIGHT SIDE RUBEN NOTICED DRIPS OF SUBSTANCE COMING OUT OF UPPER DOME DRAIN LINE.  RUBEN IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO STREET PARKING CURB OF TORRANCE BLVD.  RUBEN WALKED AROUND AND BACK TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF TRAILER AND STILL COULD SEE TRACE DRIPPINFG FROM THE DOME DRAIN LINE.  RUBEN THEN CALLED INTO JCI TORRANCE OFFICE AND REPORTED HE WAS SEEING DRIPPING OF LIQUID FROM 3404 FRP MAN WAY DRAINLINE.  ORLANDO GARCIA JCI TORRANCE BRANCH DISPATCH WAS IN ROUTE IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE CALL TO RUBEN HIS TRACTOR AND TRAILER 3404 LOCATION WAS LESS THAN 1 MILE FROM JCI TORRANCE OFFICE.  BY THE TIME ORLANDO HAD ARRIVED DRIPPING HAD ALREADY STOPPED.  I ARRIVED +/- SEVEN MINUTES LATER AND NEITHER ORLANDO NOR DRIVER RUBEN COULD DETERMINE HOW THE DOME HAD GOTTEN LIQUID WITHIN.  WITHIN A MINUTE I HAD FIGURED OUT WHAT HAPPENED.  THE TANKER HAD EXCESS OF +/- 40 PSI WITHIN.  I COULD SEE THE PRESENCE OF THE MOISTURE, I THAN OPENED THE "AIR EXHAUST" VALVE OF BULK TANK AND WAS EVIDENT THAT AIR PRESSURE WAS PRESENT WITHIN 3404.  WHAT HAD OCCURED WAS TRAILER 3404 HAD BEEN SITTING IDLE IN TORRANCE TRAILER STAGING AREA FOR OVER 24 HOURS FULL OF 12.5% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  WITH TEMPERATURES EXCEEDING 80 DEG THE PAST 24 HOURS SODIUM HYPOCHOLRITE HAD PRESSURIZED THE TANK VERY CLOSE TO ACTIVATION OF THE PRV.  WHEN RUBEN HAD APPLIED BRAKES AT STOP LIGHT ON CORNER OF DENKER STREET AND TORRANCE BLVD, THE SURGE AND PRESSURE WITHIN THE 3404 EXCEEDED THE 40 PSI ACTIVATION POINT FOR PRV TO MOMENTARILY OPEN.  I HAD RUBEN GO AROUND THE BLOCK AND BACK INTO JCI TORRANCE FACILITY AND SCALE HIS TRACTOR AND TRAILER THE WEIGHT WAS IDENTICAL TO WHAT HE HAD ON HIS MANIFEST....A GROSS WEIGHT OF 76,820
column169: RUBEN BOBADILLA DID NOT FOLLOW PROPER PROCEDURE PRIOR TO DEPARTING JCI TORRANCE TRIP.  DURING HIS "PRE-TRP" HE IS TO CHECK THE "AIR EXHAUST" VALVE OF BULK TRAILER TO ENSURE THERE IS NO PRESSURE WITHIN THE TANKER.  RUBEN BOBADILLA WAS TRAINED OF THIS PRE-TRIP TASK AUGUST 5, 2013.    FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT PRODUCTION MANUAL WAS REVISED TO EMPHASIZE PRE-TRIP REQUIRMENTS.  THIS REVISED PRE-TRIP REQUIRMENT WAS ADDRESSED DURING OCT, 2013 DRIVER SAFETY MEETING.

RAILCAR #FURX 123305 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP ON 10.10.2013 AT 0451 HOURS AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) BLUE ISLAND YARD, RIVERDALE, ILLINOIS.    TRACK WAS LOCKED OUT AND CAR PLACED IN ISOLATION. OPERATION CENTER CONTACTED "SUNPRO SERVICES" FOR RESPONSE AND UPON ARRIVAL CONFIRMED LEAK FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE AS EVIDENCED BY EXCESSIVE DETERIORATION OF SAME. ADDITIONALLY IT WAS NOTED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT SEATING WHICH RESULTED IN LEAKAGE. "SUNPRO SERVICES" REPLACED GASKET IN BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND STOPPED LEAK.    CAR WAS PLACED ON HOLD PENDING FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL DO TO DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. APPROVAL WAS SUBSEQUENTLY OBTAINED 10.11.2013 UNDER FRA # 13100682 FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE, "WOLF LAKE TERMINAL"
column169: BASED ON THE RAILCAR CHECKLIST PROVIDED BY KMTEX INDICATING THAT THIS CAR WAS IS GOOD ORDER FOR MOVEMENT IN TRANSPORTATION AND SUBSEQUENT FINDINGS OF "SUNPRO" SERVICES OF A DEFECTIVE GASKET THAT ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP SUGGESTS A BETTER INSPECTION SHOULD HAVE NOTED THAT THE GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE. RECCOMENDATIONS TO ALL INVOLVED IN RELEASE OF THIS CAR IS TO REVIEW  ALL PROCEDURES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: On 10/19/2013 at aprox. 22:00 (clear night), driver was travelling North on Rte 301 when he became distracted by a deer, oversteering to the right to miss it.  The drivers unit left the roadway and traveled through a culvert and a large ditch in a field.  In the process of travelling through the ditch in the field the trailer came loose from the truck overturning in the field. The trailer shell was punctured slightly from the landing gear, resulting in 500 gallons of gasoline to leak out of the trailer into the field. The road was closed for 9 hours to allow emergency responders time to respond to the incident. The contaminated soil was removed from the spill site and replaced with clean soil.

column17: UNITED PARCEL SERVICE OASIS SUPPLY CORPORATION
column168: WHILE LOADING A TRAILER AT THE UPS GRANDE VISTA FACILITY IN VERNON, CA, UPS EMPLOYEES NOTICED FLAMES IN THE PACKAGES NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE TRIGGERED FACILITY SPRINKLERS AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE FACILITY, WHICH WAS EVACUATED FOR APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES.  THE TRAILER WAS SUCCESSFULLY PULLED AWAY FROM THE BUILDING THEREBY LIMITING FACILITY DAMAGE.  AFTER THE FIRE WAS COMPLETELY EXTINGUISHED, UPS PERSONNEL LOCATED IN THE DEBRIS A NON-SPILLABLE LEAD-ACID BATTERY WITH UNPROTECTED TERMINALS THAT PROTURDED ABOVE THE BATTERY.  THE BATTERY EXHIBITED SIGNS OF EXTREME HEAT DAMAGE AND IS SUSPECTED TO HAVE TRIGGERED THE FIRE THROUGH A SHORT CIRCUIT OF ITS UNPROTECTED TERMINALS, POSSIBLY BY PUNCTURING THE PACKAGING AND CONTACTING A CONDUCTIVE SURFACE.
column169: TERMINAL PROTECTION OF BATTERIES IS ESPECIALLY IMPORTANT FOR SAFETY.

RESPONDER BILL DERER PROCESSED SPILL. SOLIDIFIED MATERIAL FROM PUNCTURED CONTAINER WITH UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT USING DT/RS WEARING FULL PPE. CHEMICAL REACTION OCCURRED CAUSING EXTREME HEAT FROM THE PKG, WHICH MELTED GREEN BAG, & SPILL TUB. WHITE SMOKE CAME FROM BAG, & STRONG ODOR. CHSP SUPERVISOR CRYSTAL TRACY WAS NOTIFIED BY BILL DERER. PKG WAS MOVED OUTSIDE TO WELL VENTILATED AREA. OUTSIDE RESPONDER ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCT SERVICES WAS CALLED TO RESPOND PER INSTRUCTIONS ON DT/RS. CHSP MANAGER JOANNA CORNELL, & PE SPILL COORDINATOR DAVE HOOVER WERE NOTIFIED. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY OUTSIDE RESPONDER, AND PROCESSED ON MONDAY THROUGH DMP USING DT/RS & PPE BY RAZZANO & TRACY.
column169: DO NOT EVER MIXED AN ORGANIC PEROXIDE OR OXIDIZER WITH APPROVED UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT A CHEMICAL REACTION ALWAYS OCCUR!CAUSING UPS TO CALL AN OUSIDE RESPONDER. THIS IS THE 3RD HMIRR IN A YEAR AND A HALF DUE TO FOLLOWING THE RESPONSE ACTION STEFOR AN ORGANIC PEROXIDE. THE MSDS FOR THESE MATERIALS SAYS TO SOLIDIFY THE SPILL WITH EARTH OR AN INERT MATERIAL. IT DOES NOSAY APPROVED UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT MY CONCERN IS THAT THERE IS SOMETHING IN THE UNIVERSAL ABSORBENT THAT WE USE THAT ISCAUSING A CHEMICAL REACTION WITH THESE TYPES OF SPILLS.

column168: EMI JOB #34514: ON WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 16, 2013, AT APPROXIMATELY 1652 HOURS (CTZ).  MR. TIRSO BELTRAN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. (EMI) RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. MATTHEW BERGEN  OF CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC. (CTI) MR. BERGEN INFORMED MR. BELTRAN THAT MR. DAVID KUYPERS (CTI DRIVER) HAD REPORTED THAT A 55-GALLON OF UN1899, RESIN SOLUTION (FLAMMABLE) WAS LEAKING IN A CTI TRAILER. THE TRAILER UNIT WAS LOCATED AT CORGATE TA GROUP FORWARDING, 813 NAFTA BOULEVARD, IN LAREDO, TEXAS.  MR. BERGEN REQUESTED THAT EMI COORDINATE A RESPONSE TO ADDRESS THE LEAKING DRUM AND PERFORM ANY NECESSARY CLEANUP.  MR. BERGEN REQUESTED THAT EMI INFORMATION.  MR. KUYPERS INFORMED MR. BELTRAN THAT THE LEAKING DRUM WAS AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  FROM WHAT MR. KUYPERS COULD OBSERVE, THE DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED INSIDE OF THE TRAILER.  MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (USES) AND REQUESTED THAT A RESPONSE TEAM BE MOBILIZED TO THE SITE.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER AND NO STORM DRAINS OR NAVIGATE WATERWAYS HAD BEEN IMPACTED.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HAD A CRACK THAT MEASURED APPROXIMATELY TO 1.5 INCHES LONG.  APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS (16 OUNCES) OF THE RESIN SOLUTION PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE IMPACTED AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR MEASURED APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET WIDE BY 4 FEET LONG.  USES PERSONNEL THEN PLACED THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN 85-GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM.  GRANULAR ABSORBENT WAS THEN APPLIED TO THE IMPACTED AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE ABSORBENT WAS WORKED INTO THE SURFACE FLOOR TO REMOVE THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  THE IMPACTED ABSORBENTS WERE THEN PLACED INTO ONE (1) 55-GALLON METAL OPEN TOP DRUM.  PER ONSITE PERSONNEL'S REQUEST, USES INSPECTED THE REMAINING 79 DRUMS OF THE RESIN SOLUTION PRODUCT AS THEY WERE TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  NO OTHER DRUMS WERE OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING.  USES DEPARTED THE SITE WITH THE DAMAGED OVERPACKED DRUM AND THE ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM OF IMPACTED ABSORBENTS.  THE DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE USES FACILITY IN LAREDO, TEXAS PENDING DISPOSAL APPROVAL AT US ECOLOGY IN ROBSTOWN, TEXAS.
column169: Continue our ongoing efforts in driver safety/spill prevention training in efforts in preventing incidents as these from happening.

All contaminated material was containerized.

While offloading at an approved CHESI Facility, a small wet spot was noticed on the floor.  The drum was inspected and a small pinhole was noted.  The pinhole was due to aging and denting of the drum.  3 additional drums had the potential to leak due to age.  All 4 drums were overpacked.

column168: Incident was the result of several factors;  1.  Probable strap failure due to either poor rigging techniques or strap mechnically failed.   2.  Due to the aforementioned strap failure the use of the 200 foot long line caused the pallet to be tipped in such a way as to spill the content of the pallet during transit up the mountain.
column169: 1.  Purchase bulk container for battery lifts.  2.  Perform Rigging class  3.  Reduce the use of pallets for lifting whenever possible.  4.  Perform lifts with a shorter line and place further from structures.  5.  Use bag and net for battery lifts until bulk container is purchased.  6.  Perform inspection daily of lifting equipment to be used  7.  Pilots to do more work as ground crew to improve familiarity with rigging.    *These recommendations are the result of findings made by a Safety Analysis Team on 23 October 2013, that was convened at 1300hrs and attended by Ray NewComb, Douglas MacIver, Carl Svenson, Walter Archer, Alex Fouillit, Chris Thresher, and Warren Rooks.  The meeting lasted 1.5 hours and was concluded at 1430 hours.

column168: I was informed by the Linehaul Department that there was a passover trailer in the yard that was leaking, and that we needed to inspect the trailer to determine the cause.  Upon brining the trailer to the dock, it was determined that a 55 gallon drum had been damaged due to shifting freight in the trailer during transportation.  It appeared that other freight had shifted, causing the barrell to shift and break throught the pallet it was strapped to, causing a small puncture to what appeared to be the bottom of the barrell.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing of the other freight in the trailer would have prevented this.

column168: One of the 4 drums on the pallet suffered a small leak on the body of the drum when being unloaded from the IB trailer. The checker reported the leak to the IB supervisor at the time. The leak was small and contained in house.
column169: The leaking drum was placed in a salvage drum, and rewrapped to the pallet and delivered to the consignee. Abbott Labs has since contacted the 130 terminal and will advise on 10-17-13 on re-delivery of remaining 3 undamaged drums.

column168: SEE ATTACHED IOWA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT REPORT. THIS INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY 22 YEAR OLD TAYLOR MULLER WHO CROSSED SOUTHBOUND HIGHWAY 61 AT HURTSVILLE ROAD. A PREVIOUS TRUCK ACCIDENT BLOCKED OFF HURTSVILLE ROAD, SO MS. MULLER BACKED OUT ON TO NORTHBOUND HIGHWAY 61 WITH HER SUV.  MS. MULLER'S VEHICLE WAS STRUCK ON SIDE REAR PASSENGER SIDE. AS A RESULT OF HIS COLLISION, THE DRIVER OF THE NM TRANSFER TRACTOR TRAILER LOST CONTROL AND DROVE OFF THE HIGHWAY OFF THE EAST SIDE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY IN TO A CULVERT (ALONGSIDE BRUSH CREEK). THERE WAS A SEVERE IMPACT FROM THE CRASH. SEE ATTACHED PHOTOS.  VARIOUS CARGO SHIPMENTS INSIDE THE TRAILER FLEW FORWARD FROM THE IMPACT, CAUSING THE MACHINED PARTS, METAL BRACKETS AND METAL RIMS. SPILLAGE FROM DRUMS OF SEVERAL TYPES OF FLAMMABLE PAINT AND ONE INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINER RESULTED. APPROXIMATELY 385 OF FLAMMABLE PAINT WAS RECOVERED FROM THIS ACCIDENT SCENE. TOTAL SPILLAGE AMOUNT WA ESTIMATED TO BE APPROXIMATELY 520 GALLONS.
column169: SEVERAL LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT AND FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDED.  THIS INCLUDED THE JACKSON COUNTY SHERIFF’S DEPARTMENT, THE DAVENPORT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE TEAM, AS WELL AS THE MAQOUKETA FIRE DEPARTMENT. BOOMS WERE PLACED IN BRUSH CREEK TO STOP ALL LIQUID PAINT FROM ENTERING THE WATERWAYS. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 36 HOURS, A REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR FROM ILLIONIS (BODINE SERVICES) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO BEGIN FULL REMEDIATION. ALL DRUMS AND LEAKING PACKAGES, AS WELL AS THE VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. EXCAVATION AMOUNTS INCLUDED FIVE ROLL OFF BOXES. WENZEL FAMILY TOWING FROM DUBUQUE WAS CONTACTED BY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL TO BEGIN REMOVING THE CARGO AND THE VEHICLES. FULL AND COMPLETE REMEDIATION AT THE SCENE WAS COMPLETED ON THURSDAY OCTOBER 10TH. AS OF THE DATE OF THIS REPORT, THE FINAL REPORT HAS NOT BEEN RECEIVED FROM BODINE SERVICES. IT WILL BE AVAILABLE UPON REQUEST BY IA-DNR.

column168: Veolia crew packaged the Minncare waste at the customer location in Bedford, MA. The crew was aware of the possibility that the Minncare Sterilant, over time, could cause the inner containers to become brittle.  Due to this knowledge they thought it would be best to place the containers in some sort of plastic bag or liner and they placed each container into large zip-lock bags.  It appears the bags were just a bit on the small side to get a good seal with the containers inside.  During transportation the labpack piece shifted in the motor vehicle, causing the container to tip over.  It is thought that during the handling and most likely the tipping of the box, that one container cracked and the zip-lock bag did not serve its intended purpose, allowing liquid to leak out of the inner container, ziplock bag, and the outer package. Once discovered, the Minncare leaking from the container was cleaned up, repackaged, and sent for appropriate disposal.
column169: 1. The Minncare Sterilant and other solutions like this, are prone to causing integrity issues of their containers. This will be discussed in a weekly training with the group and reviewed by the safety committee.    2. The load shift or rough handling that most likely caused the cracking of the inner container is not acceptable and will be reviewed with all employees.    3. Although a good attempt, the failure to seal the container in a “liner” resulted in an inability to contain any possible spill. In the future, we will use larger ziplock or other type bags to assure the inner container doesn't leak and/or evaluate if the inner container can be changed to a newer inner container.

STEVE WAS DRIVING NORTH BOUND ON GLEN BENCH ROAD, HE WAS TAKING A LEFT HAND SLIGHT BEND IN THE ROAD HE STATED THAT HE HAD JUST CHECKED HIS MIRRORS AND WHEN HE LOOKED FORWARD AGAIN HIS TRUCK HAD LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE RIGHT (EAST) SIDE.  THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE THEN THE ROOF THEN THE DRIVER SIDE.  IT TORE THE SIDE AND BACK OF THE SLEEPER OFF OF THE VEHICLE.  WHEN THE FIRST RESPONDER ARRIVED STEVE WAS ALREADY OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND STANDING ROADSIDE. HE MADE A PHONE CALL TO DISPATCH WITH THE FIRST RESPONDERS PHONE AS HE COULD NOT FIND HIS. DISPATCH CALLED FOR EMERGENCY HELP AND THEN CONTACTED ME (STEVE HATTON). I AGAIN CALLED 911 TO MAKE SURE THAT HELP WAS IN ROUTE. DISPATCH CALLED FOR THE TOW TOW TRUCK AND MECHANIC TO HEAD TO THE SCENE, AND GET A TRUCK HEADED THAT WAY TO PULL THE LOAD OFF OF THE ROLLER TRAILER. WHEN I ARRIVED THEY WERE ALREADY PULLING AWAY WITH STEVE W IN THE AMBULANCE. I MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHERIFF AND FIRE DEPT, THEY TOLD ME THAT DEQ HAD ALREADY BEEN CONTACTED DUE TO THE VESSEL LEAKING OUT OF THE POP OFF CAP. I STRUNG HOSES OUT WHILE WAITING FOR LEON TO ARRIVE TO PULL THE LOAD OFF. WHEN HE ARRIVED WE BEGAN PULLING THE LOAD OFF. IT TOOK QUITE AWHILE TO GET HALF THE LOAD ONTO HIS TRUCK, THE MECHANICS ARRIVED (ELVIS AND EARL) THEY CUT TWO HOLES IN THE UPSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND WE WERE ABLE TO FINISH UNLOADING ALL BUT APPROX. 30 BBLS. LEON LEFT TO DELIVER THAT PORTION. THE WRECKERS THEN PULLED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER UPRIGHT, WHEN PULLING ONTO THE ROADWAY THE TRAILER TILTED AND SPILLED A SMALL AMOUNT ONTO ANOTHER PORTION OF SOIL (I BARACADED THAT WITH CAUTION TAPE). THE WRECKER HAULED THE TRUCK TO ROOSEVELT TERMINAL. I WAS ON SCENE UNTIL APPROX 4AM. LLOYD HAD GONE TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE WITH STEVE AND HIS FAMILY AS WE WERE IN CONSTANT CONTACT. THE NEXT MORNING WE CONTACTED BLUE STAKES AND LINDSEY ROUSTABOUTS. BLUE STAKES GAVE US A TIME OF 2:46 PM ON WEDNESDAY BEFORE WE COULD DIG TO CLEAN THE CONTAMINATED SOIL. LINDSEY SAID THEY WOULD BE THERE THURSDAY TO BEING THE CLEANUP. FURTHER INFO TO COME...    CONTAMINATED SOLID WAS REMOVED AND TRANSPORTED TO A DISPOSAL FACILITY. ALL CLEAN-UP WAS DONE UNDER SUPERVISION OF DEQ & TONCOUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT.

A THOROUGH REVIEW OF ALL PACKAGE INFORMATION REMAINING  PHYSICAL INFORMATION IN THE DEBRIS COULD LEAD TO THE TRACKING NUMBER FOR THE PACKAGE INVOLVED IN THE FIRE,OR THE IDENTITY OF THE SHIPPER OR COSIGNEE. UPS CONTINUES TO SEEK INFORMATION THAT WILL IDENTIFY THE SUSPECTED SHIPPER.

column168: DRIVER WENT THROUGH A CURVE ON A SECONDARY ROADWAY. THE HOPPER-BOTTOM DRY TRAILER TIPPED OVER AND CAUSED THE TRUCK TO TURN OVER. THE TARP COVERING THE TRAILER CAME LOOSE, ALLOWING THE 24 TONS OF AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZER TO SPILL INTO THE ROADSIDE DITCH. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO DEAL WITH THE CLEANUP. THE FERTILIZER PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED USING A VACUYM TRUCK.  THE RECOVERED FERTILIZER PRODUCT WAS TAKEN TO THE HELENA CHEMICAL COMPANY FACILITY IN HICKMAN, KY FOR USE AS INTENDED (APPLIED TO AGRICULTURAL CROPS). A SMALL VOLUME OF THE FERTILIZER PRODUCT WAS CONTAMINATED WITH ORGANIC MATERIAL (WEEDS, SOIL, ETC.) AND WITH LESS THAN 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL THAT WAS SPILLED WHEN THE TRUCK OVERTURNED. THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO TWO (2) SALVAGE DRUMS WHICH WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. THE TWO (2) DRUMS WERE PROFILED AND DISPOSED OF AT A PROPERLY LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY- WASTE MANAGEMENT, TUNICA LANDFILL IN ROBINSONVILLE, MS.
column169: Additional training has been provided to drivers at the facility related to routing when transporting any fertilizerproducts and/or hazardous materials. Also, a review of the equipment operated was completed and additional emphasis placed on maintaining control of the vehicles, especially the hopper-bottom dry trailers which tend to bemore top heavy and are more likely to overturn due to the high center of gravity.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Ripped or Torn
column168: ON 10/17/2013 AT 7:46 A TRUCK OPERATED BY SEVIER VALLEY TRANSPORTATION LLC WAS TRAVELLING WEST ON I-84.  THE TRUCK WAS A TRACTOR PULLING A SEMI TRAILER BEHIND THE SEMI TRAILER.  DRIVER WAS HAULING 10,000 GALLONS OF BLENDSTOCK DIESEL FORM EVANSTON, WY TO WOODS CROSS, UT.  THE LEAD TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 6400 GALLONS AND THE PUP TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 3600 GALLONS.  THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING IN THE LEFT LANE ON THE FREEWAY OVERTAKING A SLOWER TRUCK THAT WAS TRAVELING IN THE RIGHT LANE.  THE TRUCK STARTED INTO A RIGHT HAND CURVE, POSTED 50 MPH, AT APPROXIMATELY 65 MPH.  APPARENTLY THE DRIVER REALIZED HE WAS TRAVELING TO FAST FOR THE CURVE AND GOT ON HIS BRAKES HARD, CAUSING THE PUP TO TIP ITS SIDE INTO THE CENTER BARRIER AND ROADWAY.  THE OVERTURN OF THE PUP RUPTURED THE BARREL AND THE DIESEL IMMEDIATELY STARTED SPILLING OUT ONTO THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER CONTINUED DRIVING ABOUT 1/8 OF A MILE FURTHER BEFORE PULLING ONTO THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE DIESEL SPILLING OUT OF THE TRAILER STARTED BURNING IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE IMPACT AND BARREL RUPTURE.  THERE WAS STILL DIESEL IN THE PUP TRAILER AFTER THE TRUCK CAME TO A REST ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  THE REMAINING DIESEL THAT WAS BURNING IN THE PUP TRAILER CAUGHT THE SEMI TRAILER.  SVT WAS NOTIFIED BY DRIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 08:30 A.M. OF THE INCIDENT AND IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.  SVT ALSO CALLED THE UHP AND WAS PUT IN TOUCH WITH THE OFFICER IN CHARGE, L. REMUND, AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE CARGO AND GALLONS ON THE LOAD.  SVT WAS ABLE TO OBTAIN A COPY OF THE BOL FROM THE SHIPPER AND WAS ABLE TO FORWARD THAT INFORMATION IN AN E-MAIL ONTO OFFICER REMUND.  ENVORO CARE WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO OVERSEE THE CLEAN-UP.  DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE TRUCK AND THE FACT IT WAS BURNING, UHP COULD NOT GET A VISUAL ON THE TRAILER PLACARDS.  NOT KNOWING WHAT TYPE OF FUEL THE TRUCK WAS CARRYING, THEY DID NOT ATTEMPT TO FIGHT THE FIRE OR ENTER THE TRUCK CAB TO OBTAIN THE ORIGINAL BOL.  AFTER CONFIRMING THE CARGO AND HAZARDS INVOLVED WITH EXTINGUISHING THE FIRE, THE UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL AND MORGAN CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT DECIDED TO LET THE FIRE BURN IT SELF OUT.  THE FREEWAY IN THAT AREA HAS A CONCRETE SURFACE AND CONCRETE CENTER BARRIERS.  THE UTAH STATE ROAD DEPARTMENT SPREAD SAND ALONG THE CENTER DIVIDED AND ALONG THE WEST BOUND LANES OF THE FREEWAY TO SOAK UP ANY REMAINING FUEL.  A MACHINE WAS CALLED IN TO ROTORMILL SOME CONCRETE OFF A BRIDGE DECK THAT FUEL HAD COVERED.  UDOT KEPT THE FREEWAY CLOSED WHILE THEY CHISELED OUT EXPANSION JOINTS IN THE FREEWAY THAT WHERE COMPROMISED IN THE FIRE AND REPAIRED THEM.  ENVIRO CARE PUMPED THE PRODUCT OFF THE LEAD TRAILER AND CLEANED UP THE FREEWAY OF ALL REMAINING PRODUCT AS WELL AS HAULED OFF THE SATURATED SAND THAT WAS PUT ON ROAD SURFACE.  AMS TOWING HAULED THE TRACTOR AND BOTH TRAILERS TO THEIR YARD IN OGDEN AND CLEANED UP ALL THE DEBRIS FROM THE THREE UNITS.
column169: SEVIER VALLEY TRANSPORTATION LLC WAS NOT INVOLVED IN THE DECISION TO LET THE DIESEL FUEL BURN OFF.  HAD SVT BEEN GIVEN THE OPPORTUNITY TO BE INVOLVED, WE WOULD HAVE SUGGESTED THE FIRE TO BE EXTINGUISHED AND CONCENTRATE ON THE CONTAINMENT OF THE REMAINING DIESEL. IT IS SVT BELIEF THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE ROAD DAMAGED WAS CAUSED BY THE UNNECESSARY LENGTH OF TIME THE FIRE WAS ALLOWED TO BURN. SVT BELIEVES THE FIRE COULD HAVE BEEN DEALT WITH AS SOON AS UHP KNEW WHAT PRODUCT WAS ON THE VEHICLE. HAD THE FREEWAY NOT SUSTAINED AS MUCH FIRE RELATED DAMAGE AS IT DID, MAYBE THE LENGTH OF CLOSURE COULD HAVE BEEN REDUCED. SVT BELIEVES THAT THE SEMI TRAILER HELD UP EXTREMELY WELL UNDER THE CIRCUMSTANCES. NO DIESEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE SEMI TRAILER EVEN THOUGH IT WAS EXPOSED TO AN ENORMOUS UNDER THE CIRCUMSTANCES, NOTHING COULD HAVE BEEN DONE TO REDUCE THE LOSS OF DIESEL. SVT BELIEVES THE ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY "DRIVER ERROR". ALTHOUGH WE SCREEN DRIVERS BEFORE HIRING AND HAVE REGULAR SAFETY ORIENTED DISCUSSIONS AS WELL AS MEETINGS, SVT COULD NOT HAVE FORESEEN THIS ACCIDENT. SVT FOLLOWED THEIR "NO TOLERANCE POLICY" FOR AVOIDABLE ACCIDENTS AND HAS SINCE RELEASED THE DRIVER INVOLVED IN THIS ACCIDENT.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 10/10/2013, at 06:19 am, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered GATX 57409, a loaded tank car of hydrochloric acid, leaking from pressure relief device. The car was isolated and Bayer Material Science, the shipper, and IN DEM, Hendricks Communication Center, and NRC were notified.  CHEMTREC Report #2013101000042. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the tank car equipped with Pressure Relief Device had released product while the car was heading down the bowl where the tank car proceeded to hard couple at the main track. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Chad Blake, Bayer Material Science phone number: 412-777-7475. Contractor personnel decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. In addition, the tank car was recoupled to a tank car and shook around in the yard to verfy no further product release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 422  NARRI:5(5+5+0)x(2+0)=100

column168: On 10/14/2013 at 22:27 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered UTLX 207277, a loaded tank car of petroleum crude oil, leaking product from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Flint Hills Resources was notified.  Shipper representative Kurt McMillian, (cell 316-207-0486) was given the updates. CHEMTREC was notified report 2013-10-14-00198. A CSXT emergency response contractor, EP+S of Vermont, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway gasket was missing and the packing gland nut on the liquid line valve was not tight. Contractor personnel installed a new manway gasket, tightened the packing gland nut and the leak was secured.  The car was decontaminated and released for transport.    This incident did require a special switch move.    Cause Code: 207 / 5 pts and 296 / 2 pts  NARRI: 5x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 80

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 AM, ATI DRIVER, A.C. WARFIELD, TRUCK #4015 TRAILER #1616H ARRIVED AT TRUMBULL ASPHALT IN MEMPHIS, TENN. TO LOAD TYPE 4 HARD ASPHALT.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 AM, AFTER LOADING, THE ATI TRUCK PROCEEDED TO LEAVE THE TRUMBULL FACILITY. AS HE WAS LEAVING TRUMBULL, THE DRIVED NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF HIS TRAILER. HE PARKED ON A LARGE SANDY AREA AND FOUND THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE UNDERSIDE JUST IN FRONT OF THE TANDEMS. THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR AND INFORMED HIM OF THE LEAK. THE SUPERVISOR WENT TO THE SCENE TO SURVEY THE SITUATION THEN CALLED HEPACO ENVIORNMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN THE AFFECTED AREA. ANOTHER ATI TRUCK, WITH THE PROPER EQUIPMENT TO SAFELY TRANSFER THE LOAD WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. SAND WAS USED TO SLOW THE SPREADING OF THE SPILL. THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS CONCLUDED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30AM.  HEPACO BEGAN CLEANING THE SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00AM. AFTER THE TRAILER INVOLVED IN THIS SPILL INCIDENT WAS TAKEN TO A QUALIFIED MECHANINC IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PORTION OF THE UNDERSIDE NEAR A RIB WELD WAS RUSTED, IT HAD A CRACKED SEAM. THERE WAS NOW WAY TO VISUALLY DETECT THIS DISCREPANCY WITH A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OR AT THE TIME THE TRAILER WAS BEING LOADED BECAUSE OF THE OUTHER SKIN LAYER.
column169: THE TRAILER IN QUESTION IS 13 YEARS OLD. CORROSION WAS THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  THE BARREL CANNOT BE EASILY INSPECTED VISUALLY DUE TO THE FACT IT IS WRAPPED WITH INSULATION AND COVERED WITH AN ALUMINUM SKIN. ATI IS INITIATING AN INTERNAL POLICY TO PRESSURE TEST, AT DESIGEN PRESSURE OF 5 PSI, ALL ASPHALT TRANKER TRAILERS 10 YEARS OR OLDER.

column168: Upon a routine TAG inspection for tariff compliance, it was discovered that packages of hazardous paint was marked with the limited quantity markings but the shipper did not provide any hazardous documentation to support the domestic water transport leg of the transportation chain from Tacoma, Washington to Anchorage, Alaska.  The shipment was held at the discharge port until proper documentation and container markings could be completed.      Limited Quantities can move via rail and highway without hazmat documentation but when tendered to a consolidator without hazmat documentation, the consolidater moved the cargo in the manner in which he had received it.  The must be a check and reconciliation of the hazmat markings and labeling of hazardous cargo received on the loading dock with the cargo billed for water transport.

column168: DRIVER WAS TURNING NORTH FROM STATE HWY 23 ONTO STATE HWY 8 NEAR NEW TOWN, ND. THE TRACTOR REMAINED UPRIGHT AND ON THE ROAD. WHEN THE TRAILER OVERTURNED AND STRUCK THE GROUND IT CREATED A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 8 INCHES ALONG A WELDED SEAM NEAR THE READ END OF THE TRAILER. THE PRODUCT WAS UNDER LOW PRESSURE AND APPROXIMATELY 1620 GALLONS OF BUTANE ESCAPED AND DISSIPATED INTO THE AIR. FIRE RESPONSE WAS QUICK TO THE SCENE AND SHUT DOWN THE HIGHWAY AND RE-ROUTED TRAFFIC. CHS RESPONSE CREWS ARRIVED ALONG WITH CONTRACTED SERVICES TO UPRIGHT THE TRAILER AND PUMP OFF THE REMAINING 7500 GALLONS.

column168: ACCORDING TO POLICE REPORT #131028-017 AND CONVERSATIONS WITH IN-HOUSE PERSONNEL, THE FUEL TRANSPORT CAB AND TRAILER STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION OF FM 17888 AND HIGHWAY 191 TO ALLOW FOR SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC TO CLEAR BEFORE TURNING LEFT ONTO HIGHWAY 191. THE DRIVER MADE LEFT AT INTERSECTION AND CABE AND TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE WIND WAS COMING FROM THE SE AT OVER 20 MPH DURING THE INCIDENT. FOLLOWING ROLLOVER AND LEAKAGE OF FUEL PRODUCTS FROM THE TANKER, THE CITY OF MIDLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND ERECTED ABSORBENT BOOMS IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE EXISTING HIGHWAY CURBING TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED UNLEADED GASOLINE AND DIESEL FUEL AS WELL AS KEEPING THE SPILLED FUELS FROM LEAVING THE PAVEMENT. AS A RESULT OF THE QUICK ACTION BY THE MIDLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT NO SPILLED PRODUCTS LEFT THE PAVED AREAS AND DID NOT IMPACT ADJACENT SHALLOW SOILS OUTSIDE THE PAVED AREAS. THE MIDLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT REMAINED ON-SITE TO PUMP THE FUEL VOLUMES CONTAINED WITHIN THE TANKER AND ALLOW FOR THE TANK AND CAB TO BE UP-RIGHTED AND TOWED TO AN OFF-SITE REPAIR FACILITY. SCS TRANSPORTATION CONTACTED EE&G, INC. UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE RELEASE TO ADDRESS THE ENVIRONMENTAL REQUIREMENTS FOR THE INCIDENT. EE&G DISPATCHED PERSONNEL AND ADDITIONALLY CONTACTED RESPONSE CREWS FROM ECOLOGICAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE AND ALLIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TO ASSIT WITH THE CLEANUP OF THE RESIDUAL FUEL VOLUMES LOCATED ON THE PAVED AREAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF FM 1788 AND HIGHWAY 191 IN MIDLAND, TEXAS. FOLLOWING REMOVAL OF THE MAJORITY OF SPILLED PRODUCT, ABSORBENT MEDIA WAS PLACED THROUGHOUT THE SPILL AREA TO PICKUP RESIDUAL FLUIDS FROM THE PAVEMENT FOR CONTAINERIZATION AND DISPOSAL. A TOTAL OF 7.49 TONS OF ABSORBENT MATERIALS CONTAINING FUEL PRODUCTS WAS TEMPORARILY STORED/STAGED OFF-SITE UNTIL ANALYTICAL TESTING COULD BE ACCOMPLISHED AND FINAL DISPOSITION AT THE ABILENE ENVIRONMENTAL LANDFILL WAS COMPLETED. ONCE THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE, THE CITY OF MIDLAND FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED THE PAVEMENT WITH THE WASH WATER CONTAINERIZED AND COMBINED WITH THE STORED ABSORBENT MATERIALS FOR FINAL DISPOSITION.

column168: RESPONSE: DRIVER HAD A CHOICE OF EITHER HITTING ANOTHER TRUCK WITH A TRAILER (HEAD ON) THAT WAS MERGING INTO HIS LANE TOWARD HIM, OR AVOIDING THE COLLISION BY MOVING HIS VEHICLE TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID THE COLLISION. HE CHOSE TO MOVE OUT OF THE WAY. HE TURNED HIS TRICK TO THE RIGHT TO GIVE MORE ROOM TO THE ONCOMING VEHICLE. IN DOING SO, IT DID PREVENT HIM FROM HAVING A HEAD-ON COLLISION. HOWEVER, WHEN THE TIRES OF HIS TRUCK WENT ONTO THE SIDE OF THE STREET, THEY SLID DOWN INTO THE DITCH. REGARDLESS OF HIS EFFORTS, HE COULD NOT RECOVER. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET THE CAG BACK ON THE STREET, BUT COULD NOT GET THE BACK, FLATBED PORTION OF THE VEHICLE OUT OF THE DITCH. THE FLATBED OF THE TRUCK, WHICH WAS STILL IN THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE, SLAMMED INTO THE TREE WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRUCK BEING FLIPPED AND A LARGE AMOUNT OF THE CARGO ON THE TRUCK BEING SPREAD OUT ON THE PROPERTY NEXT TO - OR WITHIN 50 FEET OF - THE TREE THAT WAS STRUCK. A GOOD PORTION (BUT NOT ALL) OF THE CHEMICALS THAT WERE BEING CARRIED DID SPILL.

HOWEVER, WHEN THE TIRES OF HIS TRUCK WENT ONTO THE SIDE OF THE STREET, THEY SLID DOWN INTO THE DITCH. REGARDLESS OF HIS EFFORTS, HE COULD NOT RECOVER. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET THE CAG BACK ON THE STREET, BUT COULD NOT GET THE BACK, FLATBED PORTION OF THE VEHICLE OUT OF THE DITCH. THE FLATBED OF THE TRUCK, WHICH WAS STILL IN THE DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE, SLAMMED INTO THE TREE WHICH RESULTED IN THE TRUCK BEING FLIPPED AND A LARGE AMOUNT OF THE CARGO ON THE TRUCK BEING SPREAD OUT ON THE PROPERTY NEXT TO - OR WITHIN 50 FEET OF - THE TREE THAT WAS STRUCK. A GOOD PORTION (BUT NOT ALL) OF THE CHEMICALS THAT WERE BEING CARRIED DID SPILL.
column169: DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO FOLLOW DOT COMPLIANCE REQUIREMENTS.

column168: HILCORP REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO BREAUX PETROLEUM AT 11:45 AM CT ON OCTOBER 31, 2013. AT 11:53 AM, MR. BUD BREAUX PETROLEUM REPORTED TO MR. CHRIS CORTEZ OF ES&H CONSULTING & TRAINING GROUP (ES&H CTG) THAT THE 21, GALLON DIESEL STORAGE TANK AT THE HILCORP PETROLEUM FACILITY WAS INADVERTENTLY OVERFILLED BY A BREAUX PETROLEUM TRANSPORT TRUCK DUE TO A COMMUNICATION ERROR. DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK OVERFLOW INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE FACILITY AND INTO THE WATERWAY ADJACENT TO THE FACILITY.
column169: RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM ES&H CONSULTING SERVICES, INC. RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT LOCATION ON OCTOBER 31, 2013 TO PERFORM REMEDIAL ACTIVITIES; HOWEVER HILCORP PERSONNEL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SPILL INCIDENT BY CONTAINING THE FUEL THAT SPILLED INTO THE WATERWAY WITH CONTAINMENT BOOM UNTIL ES&H ARRIVED TO BEGIN PRODUCT RECOVERY. A DRUM SKIMMER WAS UTILIZED AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE DEPLOYED TO RECOVER THE DIESEL FUEL RELEASED DURING THE INCIDENT RESPONSE. IMPROVED OPERATING PROCEDURES WERE PUT IN PLACE TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE.
