column168: A LAVIGNE LOGISTICS, LLC(LAVIGNE)GASOLINE TANKER TRUCK STRUCK A ROADSIDE UTILITY POLE AT THE CORNER OF LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 431 AND LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 934 IN ST. AMANT, ASCENSION PARISH, LOUISIANA ON OCTOBER 28, 2013, PUNCTURING TWO TANKS AND RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1,200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE FUEL (SEE MSDS IN ATTACHMENT A) INTO THE ADJACENT STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH. ST. AMANT FIRE DEPARTMENT, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, ASCENSION PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (LDEQ), AND OMI ENVIRONMENTAL SOLUTION (OMI) PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED  TO THE SPILL INCIDENT. ADDITIONALLY, CHUCK ELLIS WITH ELLIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED BY LAVIGNE TO PERFORM EMERGENCY RESPONSE REMEDIAL ACTIVITIES FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT.    CLEAN SAND BERMS WERE INSTALLED AT LOCATIONS UP-GRADIENT AND DOWN-GRADIENT OF THE SPILL. ST. AMANT FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL SUBSEQUENTLY INTRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 50,338 GALLONS OF POTABLE WATER WITH MICROBLAZE INTO THE STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 934, FOLLOWED BY RECOVERY OF APPROXIMATELY 51,538 GALLONS OF WASTE FLUIDS (SEE NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MAINFESTS IN ATTACHMENT B)BY GATOR ENVIRONMENTAL (GATOR) ON OCTOBER 28 AND 29, 2013, IN AN ATTEMPT TO REDUCE OR ELIMINATE IMPACT TO HUMAN HEALTH AND THE ENVIRONMENT.     PPM WAS CONTRACTED BY LAVIGNE ON OCTOBER 29, 2013, TO CONTINUE THE REMEDIAL EFFORTS TO THE SITE. PPM PERSONNEL MET WITH LDEQ PERSONNEL AT THE SITE ON OCTOBER 29, 2013, TO DEVELOP A REMEDIAL ACTION PLAN (EXCAVATION OF PETROLEUM HYDROCARBON IMPACTED SURFACE SOILS IN THE STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 431 AND LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 934). PPM AND LDEQ PERSONNEL CONTACTED LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION AND DEVELOPMENT (LDOTD) ON OCTOBER 30, 2013, TO SECURE APPROVAL TO EXCAVATE SURFACE SOILS IN THE RIGHT-OF-WAY PRIOR TO COMMENCEMENT OF REMEDIAL ACTIVITIES.    PRIOR TO SOIL EXCAVATION ACTIVITIES, PPM, ALONG WITH GATOR, INSPECTED THE STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 431 AND LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 934 AND REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 10,589 GALLONS OF PETROLEUM HYDROCARBON IMPACTED SURFACE WATERS ON OCTOBER 30 AND 31, 2013 (SEE NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFESTS IN ATTACHMENT B). PPM, ALONG WITH CONSTRUCTION TECHNOLOGY(CT), SUBSEQUENTLY EXCAVATED 148,71 TONS OF PETROLEUM HYDROCARBON IMPACTED SURFACE SOILS FROM THE STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH. THE EXCAVATED SOILS WERE PLACED IN ELEVEN (11) SECURED ROLL-OFF BOXES AND STORED ON ADJACENT PROPERTY PENDING LABORATORY ANALYSIS, WASTE CHARACTERIZATION, ULTIMATE DISPOSAL AT A PERMITTED LANDFILL (SEE NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFESTS IN ATTACHMENT C).    FOLLOWING SOIL EXCAVATION ACTIVITIES, PPM PERSONNEL COLLECTED CONFIRMATORY SIDEWALL AND BOTTOM SOIL SAMPLES WITHIN THE STORM WATER DRAINAGE DITCH. THE SOIL SAMPLES WERE SUBMITTED TO ACCUTEST GULF COAST ANALYTICAL LABORATORIES (ACCUTEST) FOR ANALYSIS TO CONFIRM THE LIMITS OF EXCAVATION AND SITE REMEDIATION EFFORTS. ADDITIONALLY, PPM PERSONNEL RECORDED AMBIENT AIR MONITORING READ

column168: On 10/21/2013 at 05:50 hours, personnel in the CSXT Great Lakes Division discovered AFCX 73248, a residue tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil, leaking from the liquid and vapor valve. The car was isolated and shipper, PBF Holding Company LLC from Reynold, DE, local agencies, and state agencies were notified. CHEMTREC Report number was issued: 2013102100021. Environmental Restoration and Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that there was heavy damage to car, liquid and vapor line valves sheared off and 2-3 inches by 2  feet puncture in car. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Keith Dempsey (Telephone #: 403-804-2510). Contractor personnel fixed the problem and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was identified to be scrapped. The incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 298 + 389  NARRI: 5x(1+3+0)x(2+0) = 40

column168: DRIVER STATEMENT OF FACTS IN REGARDS TO INCIDENT THAT OCCURED AT CUSTOMER LEPRINO FOODS/LEMOORE ON 10/18/13 CHEMICAL TRANSFER DRIVER ARRIVED AT LEPRINO WEST TO DELIVER SULFURIC ACID AT 7 AM ON OCT 18TH 2013. THE BULK TANK IN WHICH SULFURIC IS DELIVERED TO HAS A 6000 GAL CAPACITY. THE LEVEL IN THE TANK BEFORE DRIVER HOOKED UP WAS 2750 GALS. DRIVER HAD 3142 IN CHEMICAL TRANSFER TRAILER WHICH SHOULD HAVE FIT INTO TANK WITH NO ISSUES. WHILE UNLOADING THE DRIVER WAS STANDING AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WERE THE VALVES ARE AT, WHEN DRIVER NOTICED THE ACID COMING OUT OF THE DOME OF THE TANK HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE. THE ACID THAT SPILLED OUT WENT DIRECTLY INTO THE CONTAINMENT TANK AND A SMALL SPLASH ON THE LIP OF THE CONTAINMENT TANK. DRIVER CONTACTED LEPRINO AND SPOKE TO ROBIN ON THE PHONE LINE (FYI PERSONAL FOR THIS PLANT ARE LOCATED ABOUT 1/2 MILES FROM UNLOADING SITE). DRIVER STATES THAT WHAT SPLASHED OUT WAS APPROX. 1/2 GALLON OR LESS. WHEN HE REVIEWED  THE MARKER ON THE TANK IT WAS AT 5750-5800 FILLED. WHEN ROBIN ARRIVED TO TANK SITE SHE TOLD DRIVER TO RINSE DOWN TANK AND SPLASH AREA AND LET DRIVER LEAVE.  (DRIVER HAD APPROX. 25 GALS RETAIN LEFT IN TRAILER WHICH WAS SENT TO UNIVAR/VISALIA TO UNLOAD) PER COMPANY POLICY WHEN A SPILL OCCUR CHEMICAL TRANSFER TERMINAL MANAGER JACK BISHOP CONTACTED ROBIN AT LEPRINO WHO STATED THAT ALL WAS OK AND THAT NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED FROM CHEMICAL TRANSFER.    NO TRANSPORTATION OR STORAGE PACKAGE OR UNLOADING EQUIPMENT FAILED. SIMPLY OVERFILLED ON-SITE STORAGE TANK DUE TO INACCURATE GAUGE ON STORAGE TANK.
column169: HAVE COSIGNEE PERSONNEL DOUBLE CHECK TANK CAPACITY PRIOR TO ALLOWING DELIVERY AND TO VERIFY REQUESTED LOAD WILL FIT INTO STORAGE TANKS PRIOR TO DELIVERY.

column168: Box with 5 - 1 gallon containers was punctured. Spill was contained and cleaned up in-house.

TRUCK WAS TURNING FROM ON RAMP ONTO HWY 15. THE REAR TIRES OF THE TRUCK SLIPPED ON DIESEL FUEL AS IT TURNED. WHEN THE TIRES HIT DRY PAVEMENT, THE TRUCK ROLED ONTO ITS SIDE. THE DOME LID ON ONE COMPARTMENT WAS PARTIALLY UNLATCHRD. THIS LET DIESEL FUEL SPILL FROM THE TANK. THE DOME LID MAY NOT HAVE BEEN PROPERLY SECURED ALLOWING FUEL TO SPILL IN FRONT OF TIRES. I AM NOT SURE THE DOME LID WAS OR WAS NOT PROPERLY LATCHED, BUT THAT IS MY BEST GUESS.    TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL THE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT PUT DOWN SAND. THIS STOPPED THE SPREADING UNTIL CLEAN UP CREW COULD GET THERE. THE DRIVER SECURED THE DOME LID AFTER HE WAS ABLE TO GET OUT OF THE TRUCK. (1-5 MIN).
column169: WE HAVE CHECKED THE DOME LIDS ON ALL OF OUR TRUCKS TO BE SURE THEY LOCK UP PROPERLY.    ALL DRIVERS NOW CHECK EACH DOME LID FOR PROPER LOCK UP AFTER NORMAL LOADING PROCEDURES (A DOUBLE CHECK).    I AM NOT SURE IF DOME LID FAILURES WAS HUMAN ERROR OR DEVICE FAILURE. A SECOND CHECK OF THE DOME LIDS AFTER LOADING SHOULD ELIMINATE HUMAN ERROR AND HELP DETECT A DEVICE PROBLEM.

column168: THE INCIDENT IS CHARACTERIZED AS AN OVERFILL WHICH OCCURED DURING A PRODCUT TRANSFER FROM THE TRANSPORT TRAILER INTO A STATIONARY ABOVEGROUND STORAGE TANK (AST). UPON ARRIVAL TO THE SITE BY THE TRANSPORT DRIVER, AN EMPLOYEE OF THE RECIEVING FACILITY IDENTIFIED THE AST TO TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO AND IDENTIFIED THE AVALIABLE VOLUME IN THE AST. THE DRIVER INITIATED THE TRANSFER BASED ON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED THE RECIEVING EMPLOYEE.    PRIOR TO COMPLETING THE TRANSFER, THE AST WAS OVERFILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS LEFT ON THE TRUCK. UPON DETECTION OF THE TANK OVERFILL, THE DRIVER COMMENCED EMERGENCY SHUTDOWN, BUT APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS WAS SPILLED, AS A RESULT OF THE TANK OVERFILL.    THE DRIVER AND FACILITY PERSONNEL APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE SPILLED PRODUCT. IN ADDITION, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (I.E., CLIFF BERRY INC.) WAS CONTACTED TO ADDRESS THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE USE ABSORBENT AND IMPACTED SOIL WAS COLLECTED AND PLACED IN A ROLL-OFF BOX AND 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE ULTIMATE DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: IT IS COMPANY POLICY FOR THE DRIVER TO DETERMINE THE AVAILABLE CAPACITY OF THE RECIEVING TANK AND VERIFY THAT VOLUME OF PRODUCT TO BE TRANSFERRED WILL FIT INTO THE RECIEVING TANK. DRIVERS WILL NOT RELY ON OTHER PERSONNEL TO DETERMINE THE AVAILABLE CAPACTIY OF THE RECIEVING TANK.

column168: BASED ON INVESTIGATION TO DATE, COMPANY EMPLOYEE WAS OFF-LOADING PRODUCT WITH ANOTHER TRUCK OFF-LOADING DIRECTLY NEXT TO HIM. THE TRUCK NEXT TO THE COMPANY EMPLOYEE DEVELOPED A LEAK AT THE OFF-LOADING COUPLING. UPON NOTICING THE LEAK THE DRIVER WENT TO SHUT OFF HIS TRUCK ENGINE. WITH A SMALL VAPOR RELEASE OF PRODUCT, THE PRODUCT WSA INGESTED INTO THE AIR INTAKE OF THE COMPANY EMPLOYEE'S VEHICLE PRIOR TO THE OFF-LOADING PROCESS BEING STOPPED. WITH THE INGESTION OF PRODUCT VAPOR, THE ENGINE OF THE TRUCK FAILED CAUSING A SMALL FLASH FIRE.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS WERE MADE TO THE FACILITY TO CHANGE THE ORIENTATION OF THE UNLOADING RACKS, SO AS TO NOT OFF LOAD TRUCK NEXT TO ONE ANOTHER. THE FACILITY WAS ALSO TRAINED IN THE USE OF THE GO-NO GO THREAD GAUGE MONITOR.

column168: Customer went through security checkpoint with his personal oxygen bottle in a carry on bag. It was not detected. He placed his bag in the overhead bin and was seated. The bag was not checked in by JetBlue at any time. At an approximate 10,000 feet the customer Richard Venaglia asked the flight attendant to hand him his bag in the overhead bin. At no time did he state what for. While walking up the aisle it was noted he was using his own POB. Flight attentant had him shut off the device ans stow back in the overhead bin. Aircraft POB was used on him in place of his. Item could not be confiscated due to the need of use.
column169: There was no way we could have used any better dilligence in spotting, reacting and reporting.
